<dl id="n36128b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36128b">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36128b"> 128(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Great Northern, Midland &amp; London / North-Western / Great Western London &amp; SouthWestern / London Brighton &amp; South Coast / South Eastern and Chatham / Great Eastern, London Tilbury / and Southend</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><i>Railways</i> &mdash; The trunk railways leaving London, with their termini, are as follows: (1) <i>Northern</i>. The <mark>Great Northern, Midland and London &amp; North-Western</mark> systems have adjacent termini &hellip;. (2) <i>Western</i>. The terminus of the <mark>Great Western</mark> railway is Paddington (Praed Street); and that of the <mark>London &amp; South-West</mark>, Waterloo, south of the Thames in Lambeth. (3) <i>Southern</i>. The <mark>London, Brighton &amp; South Coast</mark> railway has its western terminus at Victoria, and its central terminus at London Bridge, on the south side of the Thames. The <mark>South-Eastern &amp; Chatham</mark> railway has four terminal stations &hellip;. (4) <i>Eastern</i>. The principal terminus of the <mark>Great Eastern</mark> Railway is in Liverpool Street (City), the terminus of the <mark>London, Tilbury &amp; Southend</mark> railway, and St. Pancras. <small> &ldquo;LONDON&rdquo; <a name="EBLO" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBLO"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 943-944</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
